14) react will have pure functions ?..
In React, a pure function is a function that returns the same output for the same input (props/state) and does not cause side effects.
That means — your React component should only depend on what’s passed to it (props, state) and not modify anything else outside of it.
React.memo, PureComponent

15) when to useRef hook ?..
Tracking previous values
Keeping mutable state without causing a re-render
If you want to compare previous and current props or state.
Unlike useState, updating useRef doesn’t trigger a re-render, which is useful for values that change frequently but don’t need to update the UI.

16)event propogation ?.. -> 
Event propagation is the way events travel through the DOM when an event is triggered on an element. There are two main phases.
a) Capturing Phase (Event Capture)
b) Target Phase
c) Bubbling Phase (Event Bubble)

what is lexicalscope ?.. ->
Lexical scope means that a function’s scope is determined by where it is declared, not where it is called.
In other words, functions remember the variables from the environment in which they were created.
Closures in JavaScript are based on lexical scoping

17)what is object desctructuring ?.. 
Object destructuring in JavaScript is a shortcut syntax to extract values from objects (or arrays) and assign them to variables in a cleaner and more readable way

