| -------------------------- | ------- | ----------------------------------------------- |
| `mapStateToProps`          | Redux   | Map Redux state to component props              |
| `mapDispatchToProps`       | Redux   | Map Redux action dispatchers to component props |
| `mapPropsToValues`         | Formik  | Initialize form values from component props     |
| `getDerivedStateFromProps` | React   | Update component state based on prop changes    |


19) what is react lazy loading ?..
React provides the React.lazy() function to dynamically import components.
You also need to wrap the lazy-loaded component with a <Suspense> component to show a fallback (like a loader) while the component is being loaded.

import React, { Suspense } from "react";

// Lazy load the component
const About = React.lazy(() => import("./About"));

function App() {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Welcome to My App</h1>
      <Suspense fallback={<div>Loading...</div>}>
        <About />
      </Suspense>
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;


React.lazy(() => import('./About')) → tells React to load About component only when it’s rendered.
<Suspense fallback={...}> → provides a fallback UI while the lazy-loaded component is being fetched.

20) what is code splitting ?.. 
Code Splitting in React (or JavaScript in general) is a technique to split your application code into smaller 
chunks so that only the necessary code is loaded initially, and the rest is loaded on demand.
It is closely related to lazy loading but applies more broadly to bundling and delivery of JavaScript code.

------- How it works ---------

Normally, React apps bundle all JavaScript into a single large file.
With code splitting, tools like Webpack or Vite split the code into multiple bundles, which are loaded only when needed.
This reduces initial load time and improves performance.
examples : 
Route-based splitting: Load each route separately.


21) what are react profilers , react portals , renderprops ?..
1) React Profiler
A tool to measure the performance of your React components.
It helps identify which components render too often, and how long each render takes.
Usage: Wrap a part of your component tree with <Profiler> and provide a callback to log performance data.
Use case: Optimize slow components in large applications.

2) React Portals
Allow rendering a child component into a DOM node outside the parent hierarchy.
Useful for modals, tooltips, and dropdowns where you don’t want CSS overflow or stacking issues.
Benefit: Keeps modal/overlay UI separate from main DOM, solving styling & z-index issues.

3) Render Props
A pattern for sharing logic between components using a prop that is a function.
The child function receives data or behavior and renders UI dynamically.
Benefit: Reusable logic without inheritance, works well before hooks became standard.
