24) rest operator vs spread operator
Purpose: Collects multiple elements into a single array or object.
Purpose: Expands an array or object into individual elements.

| Feature       | Rest (`...`)                                    | Spread (`...`)                                  |
| ------------- | ----------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------- |
| Purpose       | Collect remaining elements into an array/object | Expand an array/object into individual elements |
| Usage context | Function parameters, destructuring              | Arrays, objects, function calls                 |
| Example       | `function sum(...nums)`                         | `const arr2 = [...arr1]`                        |
| Output        | Array or object                                 | Individual values                               |


25) map and for each ?..
26) name some array methods ?..

	push() → add element at the end
	pop() → remove element from the end
	shift() → remove element from the start
	unshift() → add element at the start
	splice() → add/remove elements at any position
	sort() → sort array
	reverse() → reverse array

Non-mutating methods (return new array or value):
	map() → transforms each element and returns a new array
	filter() → returns a new array with elements passing a condition
	reduce() → reduces array to a single value
	forEach() → iterates over each element (doesn’t return new array)
	slice() → returns a portion of the array
	concat() → merges arrays
	includes() → checks if value exists
	find() → returns first element that matches condition
	some() → checks if any element satisfies condition
	every() → checks if all elements satisfy condition

27) what is debouncing and throttling ?..

Debouncing
	Ensures a function is called only after a specified delay after the last event.
	Useful for search input, autocomplete to reduce API calls.
	Triggered once after user stops triggering the event.

Throttling
    Ensures a function is called at most once every specified interval.
	Useful for scrolling, infinite scroll, or mouse move.	


28) useDispatch vs useSelector vs useEffect with depencency array ?..

useDispatch:
	Hook from Redux to dispatch actions to the Redux store.
	Used to trigger state changes in the store.

useSelector:
	Hook from Redux to read state from the Redux store.
	Re-renders the component whenever the selected part of the state changes.

useEffect with Dependency Array:
	Hook from React used to run side effects (API calls, subscriptions, timers, DOM updates, etc.).
	Dependency array controls when the effect runs.

30) code :
Increase the counter by clicking the button in react js example ?..
	import React, { useState } from 'react';

	const Counter = () => {
	  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

	  const handleIncrement = () => {
		setCount(count + 1);
	  };

	  return (
		<div style={{ textAlign: 'center', marginTop: '50px' }}>
		  <h1>Counter: {count}</h1>
		  <button onClick={handleIncrement}>Increase</button>
		</div>
	  );
	};

	export default Counter;


